# Solving the AEMeasurable Goal in Lean 4

To prove that the intersection of two sets of random variables is AEMeasurable, we need to show that the function mapping each outcome to the intersection of the two sets is measurable with respect to the probability measure.

Let's think about how to construct this proof. We have two sets of random variables, X and Y, both of which are p- and q-bernoulli distributed on a set u. The key insight is that the intersection of these two sets will be a new set of random variables that are the logical conjunction of the two original sets.

In probability theory, the intersection of two measurable sets is itself a measurable set. This is because the σ-algebra is closed under countable intersections. Therefore, the function that maps each outcome to the intersection of the two sets will be measurable.

