Let's think of it as the complement of the set of ω such that there exists an i ∈ sᶜ with i ∈ X ω ∩ Y ω.

The set `{ω | ∃ i ∈ sᶜ, i ∈ X ω ∩ Y ω}` is the same as `{ω | (∃ i ∈ sᶜ, i ∈ X ω) ∧ (∃ i ∈ sᶜ, i ∈ Y ω)}`.

But this is the intersection of the sets `{ω | ∃ i ∈ sᶜ, i ∈ X ω}` and `{ω | ∃ i ∈ sᶜ, i ∈ Y ω}`.

We know that `{ω | ∃ i ∈ sᶜ, i ∈ X ω}` is an event because `X` is AEMeasurable. Similarly for `Y`.

Therefore, the preimage of `s` under the intersection is the complement of the intersection of two events. Therefore, it is an event.

